      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal on your student loan statement is a common sight, even for the most diligent of borrowers. It's like trying to fill a giant, slow-moving river with a tiny bucket. The interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance, so as you make payments, the interest is calculated on a smaller and smaller amount each month. It's like trying to fill a bucket with a hole in it – the water (or in this case, interest) seeps out faster than you can fill it. The feeling that nothing is happening is just the slow, steady trickle of interest being added to your balance. But don't worry, every payment you make is like a brave knight slaying goblins, slowly reducing the overall debt. Keep at it, and you'll eventually see the principal decrease more noticeably.",
